node.text:
My mind was always fixated on grand adventures and bucket list journeys. Now I'm confined to all that is within just 5 km of my home.‚†Ä

Yet there is infinite beauty within this tiny radius. ‚†Ä

The clouds race past, their webs swirling into never-ending shapes.‚†Ä

Bees hover between the yellow flowers in our overgrown lawn in search of pollen (in a house without gardening equipment or parental visits, the lawn has grown beautifully unruly). ‚†Ä

A gangly egret balances beautifully on a thin branch over a creek, graceful despite its scrawny legs, while a black swan shakes its wings in the wetlands nearby.

A magpie couple, mum-and-pop, comb our lawn looking for the perfect twigs to build their family home in a nearby tree for spring.
‚†Ä
On the local beach, waves foam and bubble, creating kaleidoscopic colours the moment they break, while the golden orb of a dusk sun glints off my winter gumboots.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Deprived of grand overseas adventures, I'm taking another journey, an unexpected one, into the micro details of the natural world that's around us all the time. And it's equally wondrous.

#SundayFunday 

Lockdown, a forceful situation of stay at home. In the start almost all households did the entire house cleaning.

Lockdown also indirectly or directly meant a boom in digital marketing. Many people started their YouTube channels 

Lockdown also meant quite a free time available at hand for fulfilling old desires and indulging in hobbies which one never had time for during the busy schedules of the old normal 

Lockdown brought out the best of cooking skills in limelight... almost all social media platforms were flooded with photographs of people showcasing various recipe preparations

Lockdown meant an increase in household work, increase in stress of work-life balance, reduction in fat burning exercises, an increase in waist lines, etc 

With almost no source of entertainment, one finds solace in food... As a common human mentality one wants to try out new things atleast once, especially if made by friend or neighbour then it becomes imperative by most to prepare that dish... 

isn't this a common scenario... Just thought of penning down my thoughts this sunday... Would love to know what new have you tried in this Lockdown...

My Garden Thief
_________________________________________________
By the way, Squirrels symbolizes someone special to me, whom I am missing most. Trying to remain mature, understanding the need of hour - distancing ourselves with our loved ones for mutual protection. But long distance are always adventurous and requires patience. Waiting for the storm to pass and sunshine to return glittering the blue sky and welcoming us with garlands of Rainbow.
"JUST CLINGING ON..........."

We are already half way in this year and there are a lots of strong emotions running through all the time, everyday there is a new event, a new humdrum.
To touch the inner nerve and feel back the old slow rhythm, Lootera is a beautiful getaway - well not, physically but atleast in your thoughts.
I have always been in love with the songs of this movie, Zinda being my favourite. This is the song which made me respect Amit Trivedi and his creativity. 
And now, I love this movie too. Apart from being in the backdrop of early Independent days of India, having the taste of local culture and heavenly beauty, the lingering thought of a masterpiece keeps you hooked up. And towards the end, this masterpiece and it’s symbolism just sweeps you off the floor... 

Varun or Atmanand, our hero - he only knows how to draw a leaf and he makes sure that he changes the entire landscape by drawing it..üçÇ

It’s amazing what love can do to us and what we can do for it... ü§ç

node.text:
POTATO  POTAHTO
TOMATO  TOMAHTO

This English standard American-style was established in 1828 (thank you, Noah Webster) while John Quincy Adams was US president.

The British English standards were established earlier in 1755 (thank you, Samuel Johnson) while George II was king of England.

But to this day we confuse our colors with colours, our amid with amidst, our theater with theatre and still mix up our double quotes with the single quotes.

As Irish poet and playwright Oscar Wilde put it, "We have really everything in common with America nowadays except, of course, language." "The Canterville Ghost" is where that quote comes from.

Art¬†Kati Szilagyi from Babbel Magazine

node.text:
This lockdown has tested us all. üò∑

Prior to the lockdown, we would only spend the weekends together.

When I'd wake up in the morning, my sister would be at school already.

I would leave for work with Dad and spend at least 13 hours outside home.

When I would be back, it was night already and time to rest.

This was how it went on for 5 days every week, until it's the weekend.

Ever since this March, things have forcibly changed.

As of now, I've spent all these 5 months with and around them. (except when I sleep)

And let me be honest, it's not always been a joy ride.

My parents and I usually don't have similar views on a lot of subjects.

My sister is 10 years younger to me, and is currently studying for her 10th grade boards, online of course!

That makes us a mix of almost 3 different generations.

At least one of us loses mind and throws tantrums in some form or the other every day.

Earlier, these moments would either end up into blame games or most of the times into long periods of social distancing.

But now, we've learnt to understand each other.

This period has forced each one of us to build patience and be more tolerant towards each other.

In a way, social distancing has reduced the social distance between us and strengthened our bond of love.

Of course, we still each have our moments from time to time, but the love that we share wins, almost all the time. ‚ù§

Q: The most important lesson I’ve learned as a musician:
A: Read the notes correctly and then record, listen, correct and then improve it. Different room, different sound: The tempo or the length of single note can be adjustet by the pianist. He should not only focus on piano works but also on symphonies and operas to improve the sensitivity of music. Always tune the piano; don't let the piano sound like a chambalo!
.
Q: My dream performance would be...
A: ... playing Bach's Goldberg Variations in every church üïç

node.text:
CHOCOLATE TRUFFLES
.
Lotus Biscoff has a knack for effortlessly weaving it’s way into almost every dessert or any sweet fix going on in my kitchen. I used dark chocolate for a deep chocolatey richness, crushed the biscuits for a chewy texture, then laced the balls with this insanely good Belgium spread which lends a caramel fudgy finish. This is dangerously yum, legal and completely irresistible.
.

node.text:
(2/2)"All we demand is empathy when the extent of the disease goes beyond the scope of our best possible management, a little space for cremating our brothers who succumb to the virus while saving your life, a little space for our resident doctors to stay in your neighborhoods, that is all!
Working in a small covid centre I go thorough immense sufferings which goes beyond any normal 
humans understanding, but I would always wake up the next day even stronger and even better than the previous day thinking about my fellow brethren, working in huge covid centers where they are put 
through worse. 
We are all sailing in the same boat brothers, cos covid19 knows no geographic, social or professional barriers. Yet we remain perched on the front lines with the PPEs, not just to protect ourselves but to keep ourselves ready for the next set of hundred odd cases that’s about to hit the casualty and suit up to 
wage another battle against the invisible.
In this battle the plight of a surgeon in particular is a peculiar one. We surgeons are trained to attain the ultimate three all during our residency, viz Eagles eyes, lady’s finger, and a lions heart. We are made into the ultimate endurance material to withstand hour long surgeries right from word go. 
We are given the toughest job of holding the retractors for 6 to 8 hrs long for major surgeries and the bed side duty that follows that night is all together a different story. 
It has been 6 months since I placed my scalpel on a surgical case and my heart yearns for that and that only. Surgery for me is not another ordinary field, it is my life’s passion, my life’s ultimate desire, the very juice that keeps me alive. Yes! this is no exaggeration, there are people like me whose interest for surgery goes way beyond our interest for studying medicine developed. 
All we want is you to wear a mask and protect."

@casanova_kelly_weaver It’s the suicides that I’m really concerned about as well. That and the serious damage this lockdown has done to our economy. When Dan Andrews stood up at that press conference and announced the lockdown stage 4, adding that it would mean another 250,000 jobs lost like it was just an afterthought, all I could do was shake my head with disbelief.

I read that suicides currently outnumber covid deaths by 7 times. This is what really bothers me,  is the blanket lockdown approach.  There are people who can cope fine and others who can't at all. I think we will look back in a few years and shake our heads at how this has been (mis) managed.

We're all trying to deal with this as best we can. With numbers increasing in our area it seems these restrictions will go on forever.  It will test our resilience but we will come through.  We've been spoilt  as most of us haven't had to endure wars, depression or famine. Our parents, grandparents endured much more hardship and very rarely spoke of it, just simply appreciating what  they  have now. The world will never be the same and we will adjust to it.
@northwestlearningnetwork That’s true. It’s been an unusually stable period of time in Australia for the last 50 years.

Oh I know through my family that’s it’s so terrible there for you all but goodness I laughed out loud at the end of this post.  God love ya and your sense of humour sweets they can’t take that üíôüòò

Thsts why these lockdowns have been so frustrating they keep pushing back the end date.  The tests are not 100% accurate & people have no way to relieve stress & do fun stuff while risking job layoffs.  That's a powder keg.
Yes. I find Australia to be imposing some illogical, draconian measures.
I am honestly terrified of what this world is becoming. Hope it gets better for you all sooner rather than later üôè Hang in there!

Heartfelt post. I am thinking about this a lot as we are preparing for harder restrictions in NSW. The hard lockdown needs to be short and sharp (like NZ did), it’s not a long term method for all the reasons you listed. I would really like to see all the states agree on similar rules and advance testing. Better sick leave for workplaces and stop mucking around with aged care. It’s laughable how the public line is that we’re apparently protecting the economy or killing the economy when the only people being protected are the heads of those in charge.

@killarachronicles we’re in a similar situation in that we were already homeschooling, gardening, etc before lockdown, so our actual daily life hasn’t changed much. I really feel for people who live alone and are truely isolated during this time.

@ahousenamedjoy we often say the same, the immense loneliness some must feel or without fresh air and a little patch of grass to get outside onto... without children or animals to care for. It really brings it home what a privilege it is to have a family to serve.

I feel the same wondering about the outcome and what it will push people, particularly Victorians, to the brink of and where the Lord’s hand in all of this will be revealed or rather when... And the kitchen and the garden, the children, the animals all keeping a humming central rhythm to my days that I think I would certainly be less mentally even without! I’m grateful that we were rooted in this way of life beforehand, it further affirms for us that we are on the right path for our family.

Day 31 of Lockdown Round Two. 
Well, that’s a full month done of being in lockdown. Three weeks in, our restrictions were tightened, and the ‘end date’ was pushed out by another three weeks. At this point I’m assuming we will either be in lockdown forever or it will end with riots in the streets. You can’t keep a city living under some of the harshest restrictions in the world forever, eventually people will crack. 

When one has little freedom, the things that become the highlight of the day may seem silly to those enjoying a more normal existence. My highlight today was buying a ten kilogram container of yogurt for eight dollars. That kept me busy in the kitchen for the afternoon - making labne, baking an orange and yogurt cake, and trying to find enough glass bottles to store the remainder in. My kitchen is my happy place (equal with my garden!), and it’s where you’ll most often find me. (Although perhaps from this particular kitchen photo you’d assume I’m most often found in front of our liquor cabinet. If this lockdown lasts much longer that may become true.)

node.text:
When we were giving the test, only I had a symptom of "loss of taste and smell" since 7 days.
After 2 days of depression  it gave us another shock, this time my brother's life was at stake.  Management was sorry because even after waiting for 2 days, my and dad's report wasn't available.
Management kept on asking us for our swab repeatedly, that was the most irritating part. We thought how irresponsible these people are. But still we gave our swab. This time my father was saying bye to me, yet there wasn't a single word about my report.
But fortunately, I was taken to the hospital with them and I was admitted too. We all were later given the same room. This made us happy and worry a little less.
While we were at the hospital, the staff there was pathetic so we decided to go to our another centre as we weren't allowed to be home quarantined.
Only thing I realised that its upto us, how strong our will power is to get well soon and go back. It is what makes us strong.
I request everyone out there not to panic because of this virus. Everything you need is a moral support and love because the disease can be cured but not the mental instability.
Well, as everything ends with a vote of thanks and expressing gratitudes for the people that showed their support throughout. I would like to thank each and everyone who helped us through this situation and motivated us to fight it.
Blessed to have you all as a part of our lives.‚ù§

@_sakkii16 writes #audiencewrites -"An Arduous Battle"

Hello everyone,

This is Sakshi Toshniwal, from Gangakhed and I am here to share my experience after being tested positive for the corona virus.

 Everyone knows that this virus has stopped our lives and I am pretty sure that everyone is taking all necessary precautions to not let this virus enter our body. The same way even we took precautions but how did it entered our body is a question for us too! 

It was a fine morning until I realised that it wasn't fine, I saw my mom lying there, with her body temperature elevated and severe cough. It was that moment I realised that I am doomed.

Firstly, we all were under the impression that it could be normal cold but at the back of the mind we were very very scared.

Since considering it as a viral we started normal treatment but that was something I still regret because her condition was deteriorating like my mark's.

Other day we consulted a doctor who asked us for her X-RAY. 

Then seeing the X-ray, doctor said she is positive for the virus  but get her CT for confirmation. I was like anything but corona.

My dad took her  for CT scan and after seeing the report it was one more step towards the grave. We all were shocked hearing about her reports.

And then, we took the decision to shift her to a hospital . She was  in ICU for almost 5 days and when she was tested for corona , yet the results were the same. The day she was admitted, she was kept in covid ward under observation. And she started to feel better and there was recovery and that moment I realised that God does exist. Meanwhile, rest of the family was quarantined  as we were also asked to get our test done.
